 War and Reconstruction era by charting the ways in which the needs, interests, and experiences of going to war, fighting it, and making sense of it informed and directed politics, public life, social change, and cultural memory after the war’s end. In doing so, it shows that “the war” did not actually end with Lee’s surrender at Appomattox and Lincoln’s assassination in Washington. As the contributors show, major issues remained, including defining “freedom”; rebuilding the South; integrating women and blacks into postwar society, culture, and polities; deciding the place of the military in public life; demobilizing or redeploying soldiers; organizing a new party system; and determining the scope and meanings of “union.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh1 aAndrew Jr., Rod, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAstor, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCimbala, Paul A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmberton, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaulkner, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrisby, Derek W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubbs, G. Ward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Anne E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Randall M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNystrom, Justin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorey, Margaret M.,